WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.070
&gt;&gt; So I would like to introduce Alan Pearsall
who did the mural we have in our game room,

00:00:10.070 --> 00:00:16.201
which is a Fenway mural with sort of a squished
perspective of the Boston skyline behind it.

00:00:16.201 --> 00:00:21.110
For those of you on VC or watching this on
video, I think you can see a picture of the

00:00:21.110 --> 00:00:27.930
mural in progress on the GoBoston website.
It's also in Alan's website. I'll let him

00:00:27.930 --> 00:00:31.500
say what that is.
&gt;&gt; PEARSALL: All right.

00:00:31.500 --> 00:00:38.520
&gt;&gt; He's going to talk about his book about
Ipswich, which I guess started when he agreed

00:00:38.520 --> 00:00:43.120
to do a mural for them, which took about three
years to do, and so the book in total has

00:00:43.120 --> 00:00:47.360
been a five year work in progress. I'll hand
it over to you.

00:00:47.360 --> 00:00:54.850
&gt;&gt; PEARSALL: Thank you very much. All right,
well, the book, the inspiration for the book

00:00:54.850 --> 00:00:59.120
was the mural, and so I'll start with that.
I'll tell you about the making of the mural

00:00:59.120 --> 00:01:05.030
and then give you a few stories of the reason
why picked the history theme in Ipswich because

00:01:05.030 --> 00:01:09.670
it's one of the earliest towns of America
and it was an Indian village for thousands

00:01:09.670 --> 00:01:15.000
of years. But if you turn to page seven-—you
guys all have your books, so-—you can see

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:21.740
what the mural looks like in its finished
state. It's 2,700 square feet and it took

00:01:21.740 --> 00:01:29.149
me three summers to paint. Each summer I did
about a third of it, and I could paint from

00:01:29.149 --> 00:01:35.090
about May till about the end of October. And
the weather has to be at least 50 degrees

00:01:35.090 --> 00:01:43.069
or higher for the paint to cure so, you have
to do it in pieces. So, like I said, that

00:01:43.069 --> 00:01:47.889
high point there where the sculpture is, that's
37 feet high to give you an idea. And that

00:01:47.889 --> 00:01:52.369
front, those three arches are 60 feet wide.
And the folks in the front are life-sized,

00:01:52.369 --> 00:01:58.249
just to give you an idea of the scale. And
so what happened was I went in and they gave

00:01:58.249 --> 00:02:03.179
me the contract. I showed them my art work.
That's usually how I do it. And they wanted

00:02:03.179 --> 00:02:09.970
to do a large picture of a lobster--that was
their idea--and I thought that was okay, but

00:02:09.970 --> 00:02:16.540
Diego Rivera being my hero as a mural painter,
I said, well, let me try a little historical

00:02:16.540 --> 00:02:23.260
idea, and I went to EBSCO with the sketches.
If you to page 191 and 190, you can see the

00:02:23.260 --> 00:02:27.840
pencil sketch. This is the first sketch I
presented. Well, it's kind of the second version

00:02:27.840 --> 00:02:32.959
of it, but--and you can see the little squares,
as I do my sketches, an inch equals a foot,

00:02:32.959 --> 00:02:37.230
so that kind of gives you a kind of an idea
of the scale when it's all done, so. So, once

00:02:37.230 --> 00:02:42.410
I got this approved, I went to the historical
society and the old ladies there, they looked

00:02:42.410 --> 00:02:47.129
at it and they actually had a couple of changes,
you know. I really did my research. And if

00:02:47.129 --> 00:02:52.650
you turn the page, you can see the color version
of the same sketch. Then I get that approved.

00:02:52.650 --> 00:02:57.709
And I do this for every mural because—-the
same that I did for the Fenway mural here—-because

00:02:57.709 --> 00:03:01.109
it's a way, you know, not only do I use it
as my guide to paint it so I'm not deciding

00:03:01.109 --> 00:03:06.469
on colors while I'm at the wall-–it's hard
enough blowing the thing up--and, you know,

00:03:06.469 --> 00:03:10.470
you just basically just grid the wall and
repaint it, put the one foot squares on the

00:03:10.470 --> 00:03:17.359
wall and then I paint it. And on this particular
mural, I did that first archway to the left

00:03:17.359 --> 00:03:23.450
with that Chief [INDISTINCT] there. And he
went there because the president of EBSCO

00:03:23.450 --> 00:03:28.510
was a little nervous about how it would look
on the lumpy old brick. His building was built

00:03:28.510 --> 00:03:34.871
in 1826, so it had bolts sticking out of it
and there's a big line going across it. If

00:03:34.871 --> 00:03:39.739
you look at the final mural, because I hide
all the blemishes with fake ivy which I use

00:03:39.739 --> 00:03:44.079
a lot in the, you know, sculpture. So, a lot
of the times, we see the ivy everywhere. It's

00:03:44.079 --> 00:03:48.650
like it's covering up some horrible tar or
blemish on the building, but it's a good way

00:03:48.650 --> 00:03:57.519
to, you know, also it kind of makes it look
more real with the ivy. So, once I started

00:03:57.519 --> 00:04:04.299
painting, like I said, it took me three summers.
In the middle of the—-in 2006, we had the

00:04:04.299 --> 00:04:08.700
floods. I don't know if any of you guys live
on the north shore, but we had massive floods

00:04:08.700 --> 00:04:13.740
in all the rivers. And on my mural when--it's
right, probably, a hundred feet from the river's

00:04:13.740 --> 00:04:18.620
edge--the idea of the mural is there's a river
walk with a nice little bridge over the Ipswich

00:04:18.620 --> 00:04:23.699
River and the mural is the centerpiece on
the other side. Well, the water went up to

00:04:23.699 --> 00:04:29.280
six feet on my mural almost, so, pretty much
up to the necks of my people, so I had to

00:04:29.280 --> 00:04:32.590
repaint everything, because I hadn't sealed
it yet. I was only, like, in the middle of

00:04:32.590 --> 00:04:36.610
it. So, you know, I still hadn't finished
it, so I didn't put any, you know, protective

00:04:36.610 --> 00:04:42.240
coating on or anything. So I had to go and
paint that all over again. But, you know.

00:04:42.240 --> 00:04:48.819
That's quite a--well, it was the--I'm so much
faster at painting now from doing such a large

00:04:48.819 --> 00:04:53.720
project. This was by far the largest mural
I've ever done to date, and you just get really

00:04:53.720 --> 00:04:57.860
fast at it. I mean, my arm was like this one's
gigantic and this one was like skinny and,

00:04:57.860 --> 00:05:04.639
you know, this one's like a tyrannosaurus
rex. But, you know, it's tiring though, you

00:05:04.639 --> 00:05:08.360
know, so I finally, like, learned to paint
with my left hand even. I would paint, when

00:05:08.360 --> 00:05:13.000
I had a big color field, you know, I figured,
you know, [INDISTINCT], because it's really

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:17.330
large. The pictures, you know, the things,
the spaces in between things, they're a lot

00:05:17.330 --> 00:05:20.810
larger than you think. Like, I spent a whole
day painting a pillar, you know, like, just

00:05:20.810 --> 00:05:25.330
because, you know, just even doing the primer
was--it was quite a task 'cause I had to--I

00:05:25.330 --> 00:05:28.699
mean, you can see the edges are very detailed
and everything and because I kept the natural

00:05:28.699 --> 00:05:33.950
grid showing through. So, I had to do that
with the primer, paint it exactly in the shape.

00:05:33.950 --> 00:05:37.509
And, you know, you get lost in there in the
grid, you know. I've numbered it and lettered

00:05:37.509 --> 00:05:42.750
it, so I'm, like, I'm at, you know, 64, you
know, H, hopefully, you know, I think, you

00:05:42.750 --> 00:05:46.160
know, [INDISTINCT] where I've gone one down
by accident and then, you know, one of the

00:05:46.160 --> 00:05:51.370
guys, you know, he cut up a foot out of his
legs. But I have an assistant working with

00:05:51.370 --> 00:05:56.690
me and he helped a lot. He was an arts student.
And they gave me this big crane. It was the

00:05:56.690 --> 00:05:59.611
greatest thing. I looked like a cherry picker.
And I could sit in the middle of the mural

00:05:59.611 --> 00:06:03.720
and almost get to the whole mural from this
thing, but, you know, I'd be up there painting

00:06:03.720 --> 00:06:11.659
and you lose track of time. And, you know,
when you paint--that's my lawyer, I'm not

00:06:11.659 --> 00:06:15.349
here. But I was, you know, I was 30 feet in
the air and, you know, I dropped my paint

00:06:15.349 --> 00:06:20.370
brush, it goes, you know. Plus, they were
building the river walk while I was painting

00:06:20.370 --> 00:06:24.370
this whole thing, so I had a cement truck
behind me some days. I mean, one day, I'm

00:06:24.370 --> 00:06:27.340
sitting there and he's sitting right next
to me. I mean, if you've ever been next to

00:06:27.340 --> 00:06:31.349
a cement truck, it's deafening. I couldn't
hear the radio next to me on the scaffold.

00:06:31.349 --> 00:06:34.750
I go down to the guy. He's not doing anything.
I told him, "What are you doing?" He's, like,

00:06:34.750 --> 00:06:39.289
"Well, I was just watching you paint." I'm,
like, "Can you park the truck over here and

00:06:39.289 --> 00:06:44.889
then sit and watch me, you know?" But, you
know--and it was fun. As the river walk started

00:06:44.889 --> 00:06:49.229
to be built, I get the same kind of, you know,
what I call my customers going by everyday,

00:06:49.229 --> 00:06:54.479
you know, the people of Ipswich doing their
jogs or walking their babies. And, you know,

00:06:54.479 --> 00:06:59.610
I used a lot of them as my models, so, every
model in the mural is either a family member

00:06:59.610 --> 00:07:05.509
of mine because I don't have to ask permission,
I just put them in, and the EBSCO employees

00:07:05.509 --> 00:07:11.069
or Ipswich townies, and I did that on purpose.
I tried to like I have--in the strike scene,

00:07:11.069 --> 00:07:13.671
there's three cops and they're all really
Ipswich cops, but you know, they're really

00:07:13.671 --> 00:07:17.900
dressed in the times, so, you know, they had
people getting a kick out of it and kind of

00:07:17.900 --> 00:07:22.650
have a personal attachment to the mural. There's
over a hundred and twelve different portraits

00:07:22.650 --> 00:07:27.189
I did. And if you don't use real people, it
looks real fake. It looks like comic book

00:07:27.189 --> 00:07:31.389
art, you know, kind of--not comic book, but,
you know, the faces start to all look sort

00:07:31.389 --> 00:07:36.970
of the same if you don't use real models.
It makes it more authentic. What's that, Eric?

00:07:36.970 --> 00:07:43.580
Yes, actually, I did. You know, I had a lot
of baby kids in strollers going by. So, if

00:07:43.580 --> 00:07:48.520
you notice on the mural, all the cats are
kind of at that lower level so that when they're

00:07:48.520 --> 00:07:51.720
strolling along, kids who aren't interested
in history, there are at least--there's like

00:07:51.720 --> 00:07:55.780
26 cats in there or something, so, you can
count the cats if you want. Guess, you're

00:07:55.780 --> 00:08:02.110
probably looking at a nice picture of Lucy
or Otis who are very--and theme-wise I did,

00:08:02.110 --> 00:08:09.289
you can see the seasons change as I went through,
and so it could kind of give you Ipswich in

00:08:09.289 --> 00:08:16.500
every season. And the sculpture represents
the wildlife around Ipswich and stuff, which

00:08:16.500 --> 00:08:21.370
has changed a lot over the years. Back in
the day, there used to be timber wolves running

00:08:21.370 --> 00:08:25.600
around and bears and, you know, but since
we've been built up, of course, those animals

00:08:25.600 --> 00:08:30.449
aren't there anymore. I'll give you a little
update about the history of Ipswich. The reason

00:08:30.449 --> 00:08:36.350
why we chose, you know, Ipswich is one of
the oldest towns. It's only a few years older

00:08:36.350 --> 00:08:40.530
than Plymouth. In fact, even the—when they
were on the Mayflower, they sat out in front

00:08:40.530 --> 00:08:46.720
of the Cape and they're, like, "Well, where
shall we land?" you know. And by that time,

00:08:46.720 --> 00:08:53.710
a disease had knocked off about 90 percent
of the Indian population and that's why the

00:08:53.710 --> 00:09:01.060
English were able to land without very much
trouble, because they were empty. You know,

00:09:01.060 --> 00:09:06.920
Agawam, which was Ipswich, had 3,000 people
in it before the disease, and by the end of

00:09:06.920 --> 00:09:10.800
the disease they had around 400 villagers.
So, they really, you know, there were eradicated

00:09:10.800 --> 00:09:15.500
towns and Clement is actually an Indian town
called Pawtuxet that was just completely--a

00:09:15.500 --> 00:09:20.500
hundred percent of people died there. You
know, they had these fields already plowed

00:09:20.500 --> 00:09:24.830
because these were agricultural people, they
grew corn. And, I think, a lot of people think

00:09:24.830 --> 00:09:29.350
the Indians around here were nomadic because
they would move in the summer--they lived

00:09:29.350 --> 00:09:33.480
on the beaches in the summer and then the
woods in the winter because for the warmth

00:09:33.480 --> 00:09:37.220
of the trees and whatnot. It's a lot like
us now because people have the beach house.

00:09:37.220 --> 00:09:43.600
You know, it's the same thing. So, Agawam
was ruled by Maskanamet [ph], and the Indians

00:09:43.600 --> 00:09:50.330
have been living in this area for about 11,000
years. The oldest artifacts found in New England,

00:09:50.330 --> 00:09:54.720
for Paleo-Indians is actually from Ipswich
there in a place called Bolbrook (ph). I mean,

00:09:54.720 --> 00:09:59.820
this was just after the glaciers had left
and the coast was a lot close, like, in by

00:09:59.820 --> 00:10:04.870
another 10 miles. There was a big, huge fishing
hole [INDISTINCT] they found hundreds of these

00:10:04.870 --> 00:10:08.590
Paleo arrowheads, which, you know, the next
oldest, you have to go to South America so.

00:10:08.590 --> 00:10:15.690
People have loved this place of Ipswich for
such a long time. That's what's funny. You

00:10:15.690 --> 00:10:20.730
know, the English in American history, theirs
is only a few hundred years old. They just

00:10:20.730 --> 00:10:31.120
have their 375th anniversary of the town last
weekend. And if you go to page 10, you can

00:10:31.120 --> 00:10:39.690
the mural image of the town, old Agawa. Now,
Agawam, [INDISTINCT] territory is pretty much

00:10:39.690 --> 00:10:46.090
Essex County. It's the same shape, the same
borders, except at Salem and–-because Salem

00:10:46.090 --> 00:10:50.880
was a different Sagamore territory. But the
rest of Essex County was Agawam. And when

00:10:50.880 --> 00:10:56.060
they bought Ipswich, Ipswich was that whole
territory. And now there's, you know, Topfield,

00:10:56.060 --> 00:11:03.141
Middleton, Andover are now all split off from
Ipswich. But Agawam the village was the town

00:11:03.141 --> 00:11:07.080
of Ipswich, sort of like the capital of Agawam
was Agawam City sort of like, think of it

00:11:07.080 --> 00:11:12.570
that way, and, mainly, because the river ran
through there and the woods were like a wilderness.

00:11:12.570 --> 00:11:18.040
There was Indian paths, but--like they still
use today where 1A was an old Indian path

00:11:18.040 --> 00:11:22.130
that they just kept widening and widening
and widening, but that's been a road ever

00:11:22.130 --> 00:11:26.240
since, you know, for thousands of years, that
was then the coastal road. And-–but, mostly,

00:11:26.240 --> 00:11:30.020
they used the rivers as their transportation.
Same with the English did, too. They didn't

00:11:30.020 --> 00:11:35.420
have horses here on a regular basis until
into the 1700s. So, they basically took a

00:11:35.420 --> 00:11:42.190
boat or walked for the longest time. And,
like I said, the disease came and pretty much

00:11:42.190 --> 00:11:50.100
wiped Agawam, and they kind of moved their
community down into Essex, which was part

00:11:50.100 --> 00:11:55.090
of Ipswich for the longest time. They didn't
break off until the 1720s. But when Winthrop,

00:11:55.090 --> 00:11:59.210
John Winthrop, governor of Massachusetts Bay
Colony first came, he meets with Maskanamet

00:11:59.210 --> 00:12:05.040
[(ph)] on his boat, and it's probably with
the early part of dealing with--buying the

00:12:05.040 --> 00:12:13.670
land of Ipswich. In 1634, they made the deal
and they bought the--they bought Agawam and

00:12:13.670 --> 00:12:17.690
that's when they first started calling it
Ipswich. And then Newbury came the year after

00:12:17.690 --> 00:12:24.520
that. And if you go to page 14, you can see
how old Agawam looked. And the great thing

00:12:24.520 --> 00:12:31.340
about this is it's still a lot a park land.
So, on that page that's where the chief lived

00:12:31.340 --> 00:12:35.120
on that beautiful island that's kind of in
the haze in the background. And I painted

00:12:35.120 --> 00:12:41.250
that as well. This book I did many illustrations
and paintings for it. I did the maps. I did

00:12:41.250 --> 00:12:48.360
the graphic design and I wrote it, so it's
a one-man band sort of thing. So, I like to

00:12:48.360 --> 00:12:57.150
think of it as like Bowie's Diamond Dogs album.
There are Bowie fans out there. OK. Now, this

00:12:57.150 --> 00:13:02.160
book is like my masterpiece because I really
did--they were going to have someone else

00:13:02.160 --> 00:13:06.170
write it and I said, "Hey, let me try it.
I just researched this town for the last two

00:13:06.170 --> 00:13:11.060
and a half years, you know. And, you know,
so it's all in my mind. And I looked at the

00:13:11.060 --> 00:13:15.020
town, when I walk through the streets, I see
the past. You know, I can see-–it's great

00:13:15.020 --> 00:13:19.880
because they were very poor during the revolutionary
era so people didn't rebuild all the houses.

00:13:19.880 --> 00:13:24.240
So there's a ton of old--most in the county
of these first period houses, so you can go

00:13:24.240 --> 00:13:27.940
there and a lot of the streets, it doesn't
really look that different if you take the

00:13:27.940 --> 00:13:37.010
power lines down, you know. It's the beautiful
thing about Ipswich. So, by the time the English

00:13:37.010 --> 00:13:43.580
got here, like I said, it was very few Indians
left, and Maskanamet (ph) sold the land. He

00:13:43.580 --> 00:13:47.400
actually still lived here, though. And the
rulers back then were like--the Indians were

00:13:47.400 --> 00:13:53.600
allowed to still hunt on the land that they
sold so there was no real friction between

00:13:53.600 --> 00:13:57.420
the Native Americans who lived right in this
area. And if you read old books, they always

00:13:57.420 --> 00:14:01.220
say, "Our Indians," and then "The Indians."
The "Our Indians" were the ones that actually

00:14:01.220 --> 00:14:05.660
lived with them. The Indians they had trouble
with were like the New Yorkers. The Boston

00:14:05.660 --> 00:14:10.110
against the New Yorkers has been going on
for thousands of years. The Iriquoi against

00:14:10.110 --> 00:14:18.550
the Algonquin. They were [INDISTINCT] till
recently. That's a funny comment I've made.

00:14:18.550 --> 00:14:21.890
One of my Indians is Johnny Damon (ph). If
you look close at the mural, he's the guy

00:14:21.890 --> 00:14:25.800
right in the corner next to the pillar, it's
Johnny Damon (ph) because he looks sort like

00:14:25.800 --> 00:14:30.380
a Native American to me. I'm sure he like
Italian or something, but that was before

00:14:30.380 --> 00:14:35.760
he defected. You know, his hair is long, I
had no idea he was going to quit the team.

00:14:35.760 --> 00:14:42.420
But if you go to page 58, I did an illustration
of Ipswich in the 1650s. And you can kind

00:14:42.420 --> 00:14:49.270
of see what kind of a little town it was.
And I took a map from 1915, and I have old

00:14:49.270 --> 00:14:54.020
maps that are hand-drawn and things and tells
me all the locks and stuff. And the great

00:14:54.020 --> 00:14:58.860
thing is, you can look at this overhead view
of the modern map, there's actually still

00:14:58.860 --> 00:15:04.730
several of the houses still existing from
this era, but also the plots have only been

00:15:04.730 --> 00:15:09.570
split or quartered, you know, but they're
still the same land plots that were originally

00:15:09.570 --> 00:15:13.730
divvied out by the governor's son who was
the founder of Ipswich, John Winthrop, Jr.

00:15:13.730 --> 00:15:22.220
And the governor himself went to Ipswich's
first year [INDISTINCT] his son had his grandson,

00:15:22.220 --> 00:15:27.440
so the governor walked from Boston to Ipswich
because, of course, there was no-–he didn't

00:15:27.440 --> 00:15:31.570
have any horses, so he walked. You know, when
I was trying to get the governor to come to

00:15:31.570 --> 00:15:34.610
the thing this weekend, I said, "I'm telling
you, you could take a car, the first governor

00:15:34.610 --> 00:15:42.410
walked here." You know, it didn't work though.
He didn't come. All right, Ipswich has a reputation

00:15:42.410 --> 00:15:45.870
they like to brag about called "The Birth
of American Independence." And the reason

00:15:45.870 --> 00:15:52.470
why they say they that is in 1660, a bunch
of the town members had a meeting before they

00:15:52.470 --> 00:15:57.480
got this new tax levy--this was almost a hundred
years before the revolution--and they didn't

00:15:57.480 --> 00:16:01.600
like it. Ipswich was one of the most prosperous
towns. They had the only other courthouse

00:16:01.600 --> 00:16:07.680
besides Boston and jailhouse. And so they
were like at, in their heyday in the early

00:16:07.680 --> 00:16:19.570
1700s and 1600s. So, when they--it was 1698-–'89
rather, sorry, losing my memory. They had--they

00:16:19.570 --> 00:16:24.860
signed a petition to the king telling him
that they didn't want to pay this tax, said,

00:16:24.860 --> 00:16:29.720
you know, what basically happened was in England,
they had the fire that burned down all of

00:16:29.720 --> 00:16:34.110
London and they just for 60 years just left
the colonies on their own and didn't really

00:16:34.110 --> 00:16:40.320
bother them and just let them do their thing.
And so for almost three generations, they--clearing

00:16:40.320 --> 00:16:44.720
